'''Pyrolite''' is a theoretical rock considered to be the best approximation of the composition of [[Earth]]'s [[Mantle (geology)|upper mantle]]. The definition varies, but it is generally considered as being 1 part [[tholeiitic basalt]] and 3 parts [[dunite]]. If fused experimentally, this mix yields high pressure tholeiitic basaltic [[magma|melts]], and intermediate pressure alkaline basalts. The hypothetical pyrolite compositions are not compatible with [[trace element]], [[isotope|isotopic]] and [[Chondrite|chondritic]] abundances data as well as evidence for mantle heterogeneity.<ref>Don L. Anderson, ''New Theory of the Earth'', Cambridge University Press, 2nd ed. 2007, p. 193 {{ISBN|978-0-521-84959-3}} </ref>
